title: Scene02_Dialogue
---
Edmund: What...?

Narrator: Edmund eyes widen as he sees the unthinkable - Standing in the entrance hall is a man wearing Edmund's face. The stranger is speaking with the households as if he belongs there.

Guard: Halt. State your business.

Edmund: Move aside. This is my own house.

Guard: Your house? What nonsense are you spilling?

Edmund: Watch your tongue! I am Lord Edmund, heir of House Ashworth.

Guard: That cannot be. Lord Edmund returned home an hour ago.

Edmund: I am standing before you.

Narrator: The guard turns toward the manor, then back at Edmund. His grip on the halberd is uncertain, confused. Can anyone blame him in this situation?

Narrator: Then out of nowhere, lanterns approach through the fog - a dozen of townsfolk gathered. They arrange themselves around Edmund like a jury. This is clearly too convenient to merely be a coincidence.

Narrator: The guard then briefly tells them the happening. For a while, they keep whispering among themselves, but none step forward.

Narrator: Their silence feels rehearsed.

Edmund: Enough! I do not know what trick has been played here, but I am Lord Edmund, the rightful heir of House Ashworth!

Villagers: Then prove it.

Edmund: I need to prove nothing at the front of my own gate.

???: You do now.

Narrator: The figure steps forward, his hand holding a sealed writ marked with the crest of the Court of Continuance.

Accuser: By the law of Continuance, no man may possess two lives, a no house may claim two heirs.

Edmund: You brought these witnesses to my gate before i even reached it.

Narrator: The Accuser does not answer. He raises the writ instead.

Accuser: Another man has already laid claim to the heirship. Now two men stand beneath one name.

Edmund: The rail line failed before the sun even rises. And the Court does not seal a writ between dawn and dusk.

Accuser:
And yet the seal is dry.

Edmund: Then it was written before my carriage ever left the road.

Narrator: Another chilling silence... 

Narrator: The Accuser then continues as if the words had not been spoken.

Accuser: The Trial will decide the matter. Body. Memory. Chronology. By these three proofs, the rightful heir shall be recognized.

Edmund: And if I refuse?

Accuser: Refusal is a verdict. Whichever man fails to prove his claim shall be stripped of name, title, inheritance, and legal existence.

Edmund: And the one the Court rejects?

Accuser: There is no man it rejects.

Accuser: There will be a man - and a Fabrication.

Edmund: And if the Court is wrong?

Accuser: Then it will be wrong in ink, seal, and law.

Narrator: The crowd falls silent.

Accuser: By the sunrise, only one Lord Edmund shall remain.

Narrator: Edmund looks past the gate. Inside the manor, the double watches him from the warm light of the entrance hall.

Narrator: For a moment, neither man moves.

Edmund: Then I will bring you proof.

Accuser: I will see that. The Trial begins at dawn.

===
